          class="inline-flex items-center px-8 py-4 text-lg font-bold text-white bg-gradient-to-r from-primary-600 to-primary-700 rounded-xl hover:from-primary-700 hover:to-primary-800 hover:scale-105 transition-all duration-300 shadow-lg hover:shadow-xl"
        >
          Get a Free Consultation with our Preferred Partner
        </button>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-3">
          Our relocation partners with us and gives free consultations to users
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why Finance in Zurich Matters -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <div class="text-center mb-12">
          <span class="inline-block px-4 py-2 bg-primary-100 text-primary-800 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold mb-4">
            Why It Matters
          </span>
          <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
            Why Finance in Zurich <span class="bg-gradient-to-r from-primary-600 to-primary-700 bg-clip-text text-transparent">Matters for Expats</span>
          </h2>
          <p class="text-xl text-gray-600">
            Switzerland's financial capital offers world-class banking but requires local knowledge
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-50 to-white p-8 rounded-2xl border border-gray-100">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-500 to-primary-600 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M3 10h18M7 15h1m4 0h1m-7 4h12a3 3 0 003-3V8a3 3 0 00-3-3H6a3 3 0 00-3 3v8a3 3 0 003 3z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Global Banking Hub (Paradeplatz)</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
              Zurich is Switzerland's and Europe's leading financial center. Paradeplatz (Parade Square) in central Zurich houses headquarters of UBS (Switzerland's largest bank and one of world's top wealth managers), Credit Suisse (global investment bank and private banking leader), and numerous private banks, asset managers, and financial institutions. Bahnhofstrasse, Zurich's premier street, hosts flagship branches of all major Swiss banks plus international banks (HSBC, Citibank, JP Morgan). This concentration creates unparalleled banking infrastructure: expats access world-class wealth management, private banking for HNWI, corporate banking for business needs, and investment advisory. However, traditional banks often require significant deposits (CHF 50,000-250,000 for private banking), employment contracts, and in-person meetings. Neobanks offer alternative with digital-first, English-friendly services accessible to all expats with residence permits.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-50 to-white p-8 rounded-2xl border border-gray-100">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-500 to-primary-600 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 18h.01M8 21h8a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H8a2 2 0 00-2 2v14a2 2 0 002 2z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Neobank Revolution for Expats</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
              Zurich expats increasingly use neobanks (digital banks) offering fast, English-friendly onboarding without traditional banking barriers. Yapeal (Swiss digital bank, FINMA-licensed) provides Swiss IBAN (CH prefix), multi-currency accounts, instant account opening via app with residence permit, no minimum balance, sustainability focus. Neon (Swiss digital bank via Hypothekarbank Lenzburg) offers free Swiss account, cashback programs, savings spaces, excellent for students and young professionals. Revolut (UK-based fintech, Swiss operations) widely used for multi-currency management, real-time currency exchange, international transfers at interbank rates, cryptocurrency, premium metal cards. These neobanks solve common expat pain points: English interfaces, quick onboarding (1-3 days vs. weeks), no employment contract required for basic accounts, low/no fees, mobile-first design. Many Zurich expats use dual strategy: Swiss neobank for salary and bills, Revolut for spending and international transactions.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-50 to-white p-8 rounded-2xl border border-gray-100">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-500 to-primary-600 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m5.618-4.016A11.955 11.955 0 0112 2.944a11.955 11.955 0 01-8.618 3.04A12.02 12.02 0 003 9c0 5.591 3.824 10.29 9 11.622 5.176-1.332 9-6.03 9-11.622 0-1.042-.133-2.052-.382-3.016z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Private Banking & Wealth Management</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
              Zurich leads globally in private banking and wealth management services. Expat professionals, entrepreneurs, and HNWI access specialized services: private banking (CHF 1+ million investable assets), portfolio management (diversified investments, tax optimization), estate planning (cross-border inheritance, trusts), alternative investments (hedge funds, private equity, real estate). Major providers: UBS Wealth Management (world's largest wealth manager), Credit Suisse Private Banking, Julius Baer (Swiss private banking specialist), Lombard Odier (Geneva-based with Zurich presence), Pictet (independent Swiss bank). Services require introductions, significant assets, and relationship management. Relocation agencies facilitate introductions to private bankers, explain Swiss wealth management approach (discretion, stability, expertise), and coordinate with tax advisors. Middle-income expats (CHF 100,000-500,000 annual income) access premium banking tiers at UBS/CS with benefits like dedicated advisors, investment platforms, and preferential rates.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-50 to-white p-8 rounded-2xl border border-gray-100">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-500 to-primary-600 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 7h6m0 10v-3m-3 3h.01M9 17h.01M9 14h.01M12 14h.01M15 11h.01M12 11h.01M9 11h.01M7 21h10a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H7a2 2 0 00-2 2v14a2 2 0 002 2z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Zurich Canton Tax Planning</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
              Canton Zurich has progressive tax system requiring professional planning for expats. Tax components: federal income tax (0-11.5%, applies nationwide), cantonal income tax (varies by municipality, 2-15%), municipal income tax (varies, 2-10%), wealth tax (0.1-0.5% on net assets in Zurich). Combined income tax rates in Zurich city approximately 25-35% depending on income (lower in suburbs like Zollikon, K√ºsnacht). Wealth tax applies to worldwide assets for Swiss tax residents. Expats must navigate: double taxation treaties (avoiding tax in both Switzerland and home country), lump-sum taxation (special regime for wealthy expats without Swiss employment, minimum CHF 400,000 taxable expenditure in Zurich), tax-deductible items (pillar 3a retirement savings CHF 7,056/year for employees, mortgage interest, professional expenses, commuting costs). Tax declaration deadlines strict (March 31 following tax year). Relocation agencies coordinate with Zurich tax advisors ensuring compliant, optimized tax strategies for expat situations.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-50 to-white p-8 rounded-2xl border border-gray-100">
            <div class="w-12 h-12 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-500 to-primary-600 rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center mb-4">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 15v2m-6 4h12a2 2 0 002-2v-6a2 2 0 00-2-2H6a2 2 0 00-2 2v6a2 2 0 002 2zm10-10V7a4 4 0 00-8 0v4h8z" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Documentation & Account Opening Challenges</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
              Opening Zurich bank accounts as expat presents hurdles. Required documents: valid passport (6+ months validity), Swiss residence permit (B, L, C, or legitimation card for UN staff), proof of Zurich address (rental contract or Kreisb√ºro residence confirmation), employment contract (showing salary, role, employer), sometimes salary slips or tax returns for premium accounts. Traditional banks (UBS, Credit Suisse, Raiffeisen) require in-person appointments at Zurich branches, may request employer reference letters, conduct AML (anti-money laundering) due diligence, and take 1-3 weeks for approval. Without employment contract or permit, account opening nearly impossible at traditional banks. Neobanks (Yapeal, Neon) simplify process: online application (5-15 minutes), document upload via app, video verification, approval within 1-3 days once permit obtained. Catch-22: employers require Swiss bank account for salary payments, banks require employment contract to open account. Solution: relocation agencies coordinate timing, facilitate neobank account opening immediately upon arrival, then add traditional bank if needed for mortgages/investments.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-12 p-8 bg-gradient-to-br from-primary-50 via-white to-red-50 rounded-2xl border-2 border-primary-100">
          <div class="flex items-start">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <svg class="w-8 h-8 text-primary-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20">
                <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M18 10a8 8 0 11-16 0 8 8 0 0116 0zm-7-4a1 1 0 11-2 0 1 1 0 012 0zM9 9a1 1 0 000 2v3a1 1 0 001 1h1a1 1 0 100-2v-3a1 1 0 00-1-1H9z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="ml-4">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Expert Insight</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Zurich offers unparalleled banking choice but requires strategic approach.</strong> Most expats start with neobank (Yapeal/Neon) for immediate Swiss IBAN and salary payments, adding Revolut for multi-currency management. Corporate expats and HNWI leverage relocation agencies for UBS/Credit Suisse introductions and private banking access. Tax planning essential given Zurich's progressive rates (25-35% combined). Insurance mandatory within 3 months; use <a href="https://expat-savvy.ch" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-primary-600 hover:text-primary-700 font-semibold underline">Expat-Savvy.ch</a> for expert guidance comparing Swiss health insurance providers.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
